It looks like the _transform property of Node is not restored once you setAdditionalTransform( nullptr ) after a previously set setAdditionalTransform( any matrix ).
The problem wouldn't show up if you were updating transforms of the node (as the transform was flagged dirty and recomputed).

So I had to add this line to make cocos2d react like it should. (restoring the original _transform without the previously concatenated additional transform matrix)

``` c++
if(_additionalTransform)  _transform = _additionalTransform[1];
```

here's the fixed function:

``` c++
void Node::setAdditionalTransform(const Mat4* additionalTransform)
{
    if (additionalTransform == nullptr)
    {
        if(_additionalTransform)  _transform = _additionalTransform[1];

        delete[] _additionalTransform;
        _additionalTransform = nullptr;
    }
    else
    {
        if (!_additionalTransform) {
            _additionalTransform = new Mat4[2];

            // _additionalTransform[1] is used as a backup for _transform
            _additionalTransform[1] = _transform;
        }

        _additionalTransform[0] = *additionalTransform;
    }
    _transformUpdated = _additionalTransformDirty = _inverseDirty = true;
}
```

